    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="165"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d165">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 PW/10–2844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-28">October 28,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1388. The White House issued the following press release at noon, October 28:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>General Stilwell has been relieved as Chief of Staff to Generalissimo
                            Chiang Kai-shek, as Deputy to Admiral Mountbatten, Commander of the
                            South East Asia Command, and as U. S. Commander of the China–Burma–India
                            Theater and has been recalled to Washington.<note n="1" xml:id="d165fn1"
                                >October 21, 1944.</note> The former China–Burma–India Theater will
                            be divided into two theaters under separate commanders. The U. S. Forces
                            in the China Theater will be commanded by Major General A. C. Wedemeyer,
                            who has been appointed concurrently by the Generalissimo, Chief of Staff
                            of the China Theater. General Wedemeyer is now Deputy Chief of Staff to
                            Admiral Mountbatten. The United States Forces in the India–Burma Theater
                            will be commanded by Lieutenant General Daniel I. Sultan, now Deputy
                            Commander of the China–Burma–India Theater.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
